{
  "doc_id": "35418",
  "text": "ERCC1 is essential for NER, in which it acts in a complex with XPF to make the incision 5′ to the lesion site. Unlike the other NER proteins, ERCC1 and XPF are also involved in homologous recombination, double-strand break repair and the repair of interstrand crosslinks. Their role in recombination was deduced originally from studies on the Saccharomyces cerevisiae homologues, RAD10 (ERCC1) and RAD1 (XPF), which are involved in both NER and mitotic recombination [CITATION_1] . In addition, ERCC1-deficient or XPF-deficient mammalian cells are characteristically hypersensitive to the interstrand crosslinking agent mitomycin C. The key role, which explains the involvement of the ERCC1/XPF complex in these different recombination-repair pathways, is the ability to cleave singlestranded 3′-tails projecting from DNA duplexes [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] .",
